      {
        "id": 2835535,
        "name": "William Kelley",
        "username": "William_Kelley",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/william_kelley/{size}/2314_2.png",
        "created_at": "2020-03-13T15:30:48.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-post=\"1\" data-topic=\"159038\">\n<blockquote>\n<p>The <strong>2015 Pierre-Yves Colin-Morey Saint-Aubin Le Banc</strong> glistens in the glass in a most inviting way. There\u2019s just the right amount of smoky mineral reduction. It is richly fruited, loaded with citrus of all persuasion. It possesses a crystalline quality and is direct, intense and finishes so fresh and bright.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>I was prompted to open a bottle yesterday on reading your note, and I agree with you entirely. Like all of Pierre-Yves\u2019 2015s, this was amazing in barrel but then shut down hard in bottle, and it\u2019s only now unwinding. When we tasted together back in 2016 PY compared his 2015s to his father\u2019s 1985s, and that may well prove quite persuasive in the fullness of time. While 2015 white Burgundies are quite short on admirers, producers such as PYCM, Bernard Moreau, Lamy-Caillat and Coche-Dury really made the best of the vintage and I am very happy to have plenty of their bottles in my cellar.</p>",
        "post_number": 7,
        "post_type": 1,
